Dear Mr. 

It was a pleasure to meet you at the Pathways to Equitable Healthy Cities
meeting at the University of Ghana. I'm sure you won't remember me, but I was
talking with you about flooding in in Accra, and the fact that in many cases the
places where flooding is likely to occur is known beforehand.

Following our discussion I did some more research on People's Dialogue, and
discovered that one aspect of your work is participatory data collection, which
you use to advocate on behalf of slum residents. My research group (led by Dr
Wouter Buytaert, CC'd) have been developing low cost sensors, which we have
deployed around the world. One of the things we measure is water level, which is
obviously very relevant to flood monitoring. These sensors are typically
installed above a watercourse (for example, underneath a bridge), and measure
water level every few minutes. We are working on ways to upload this data to the
internet in realtime. 

As part of the Pathways project I may have some funding available to install
some sensors in Accra. Following our conversation, I thought that it may be
useful to focus on a particular neighbourhood where flooding is known to
occur. The data should give an indication of when and where a watercourse
(e.g. a river or open drain) overflows. This data could be matched with the
experience of residents, and used to provide hard evidence of flooding in the
neighbourhood. 

Our experience is that such initiatives are only successful when the data can be
used in some useful way by the communities in which the sensors are
installed. Clearly, you have considerable expertise in using data for
advocacy. Hence, I had two questions for you:

1. Would People's Dialogue find the sort of data I describe useful?
2. If yes to (1), would you be able to help me find a suitable site for
   installing the sensors, and perhaps someone who knows the area to accompany
   me while I install them?

At this stage nothing is set in stone, so there is some flexibility about what
we could do. Given your expertise and experience in working in Accra, I would
appreciate your advice on the feasibility of the proposal. In any case, I look
forward to hearing from you.

Kind regards,
Simon
